                            <h1>
                            Content with the Things Allotted unto Us
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p3" class="">Elder Neal A. Maxwell</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/neal-a-maxwell?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/neal-a-maxwell-10.jpg" alt="Neal A. Maxwell" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        <div class="kicker" id="">Life&rsquo;s necessary defining moments come within our allotments. &hellip; Our responses are what matter. Sufficient unto each life are the tests thereof!</div>
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">20905_000_030</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p5" class="">With all of you, brothers and sisters, I express appreciation to President Hinckley for his tireless shaping of the Church&rsquo;s future, of which this Conference Center is emblematic.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p6" class="">In just a few words, a major insight came to the conscientious and the converted through Alma: &ldquo;For I ought to be content with the things which the Lord hath allotted unto me&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:3</a>). However, just prior, Alma urgently desired to be the &ldquo;trump of God&rdquo; so that he might &ldquo;shake the earth&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:1</a>). But not because of ego; in fact, Alma wanted to declare repentance and the plan of redemption to all mankind so that there might be no more human sorrow (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:2</a>). Yet Alma&rsquo;s contentment rested on the reality that God finally allots to us according to our wills (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:4</a>). What could be more fair?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p7" class="">Thus becoming content with his calling, Alma then meekly hoped to be an instrument to help save some soul (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:9</a>). A significant spiritual journey is thus reflected in but nine soliloquy-like verses.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p8" class="">The same contentment awaits us if our own desires can be worked through and aligned.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p9" class="">What some mortals are allotted includes, for instance, very reduced chances because of poverty: &ldquo;And the people began to be distinguished by ranks, according to their riches and their chances for learning; yea, some were ignorant because of their poverty, and others did receive great learning because of their riches&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/6.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 6:12</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p10" class="">Furthermore, malevolent, human social structures have included, in the past, tragic constraints like slavery and concentration camps.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p11" class="">Nevertheless, we are to do what we can within our allotted &ldquo;acreage,&rdquo; while still using whatever stretch there may be in any tethers. Within what is allotted to us, we can have spiritual contentment. Paul described it as &ldquo;godliness with contentment,&rdquo; signifying the adequate presence of attributes such as love, hope, meekness, patience, and submissiveness (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-tim/6.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Tim. 6:6</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p12" class="">Yet there are other fixed limitations in life. For instance, some have allotments including physical, mental, or geographic constraints. There are those who are unmarried, through no fault of their own, or yearning but childless couples. Still others face persistent and unreconciled relationships within their circles of loved ones, including offspring who have &ldquo;[become] for themselves,&rdquo; resistant to parental counsel (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/1.29?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 1:29</a>). In such and similar situations, there are so many prickly and daily reminders.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p13" class="">Being content means acceptance without self-pity. Meekly borne, however, deprivations such as these can end up being like excavations that make room for greatly enlarged souls.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p14" class="">Some undergo searing developments that cut suddenly into mortality&rsquo;s status quo. Some have trials to <span class="emphasis">pass through, </span>while still others have allotments they are to <span class="emphasis">live with.</span> Paul lived with his &ldquo;thorn in the flesh&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-cor/12.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Cor. 12:7</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p15" class="">Suffice it to say, such mortal allotments will be changed in the world to come. The exception is unrepented sin that shapes our status in the next world.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p16" class="">Thus, developing greater contentment within certain of our existing constraints and opportunities is one of our challenges. Otherwise we may feel underused, underwhelmed, and underappreciated&mdash;while, ironically, within our givens are unused opportunities for service all about us. Neither should we pine away, therefore, for certain things outside God&rsquo;s givens, such as for the powerful voice of an angel, because there is so much to do within what has been allotted to us (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.3-4?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:3&ndash;4</a>). Furthermore, varied as our allotted circumstances may be, we can still keep the commandments of God!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p17" class="">Meanwhile, we serve as each other&rsquo;s clinical material in the particular sample of humanity constituting &ldquo;what is allotted unto [us].&rdquo; The sample may shrink or swell, but most important is <span class="emphasis">what we are and what we do</span> within those varied allocations and in the particular &ldquo;work to which [we] have been called&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:6</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p18" class="">Thus &ldquo;the holy present&rdquo; contains the allotted acres for our discipleship. We need not be situated in prime time with prime visibility in order to work out our own salvation!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p19" class="">In contrast, however, as to improving our behavior, there are no borders that we cannot cross and no shortage of visas for those willing to venture!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p20" class="">Incremental improvement is, therefore, the order of the day, and it clearly requires the accompaniment of the Lord&rsquo;s long-suffering as we struggle to learn the necessary lessons.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p21" class="">Mary, having been told some wondrous things about herself and what lay ahead, nevertheless &ldquo;kept all these things, and pondered them in her heart&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/2.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 2:19</a>). Pondering often precedes contentment.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p22" class="">Performance is what matters, not the size of the stage. The Sea of Galilee, only 13 miles by 7, was nevertheless large enough to provide the disciples with a vital experience involving faith and walking on the water (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/14.22-33?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 14:22&ndash;33</a>). The wind was boisterous and frightening! Even so, compare the size of those Galilean swells and the length of that storm with what Nephi and party had to endure on the vast ocean! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/18.13-21?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 18:13&ndash;21</a>). Yet both episodes provided the needed learning experiences. Of course, I should be careful about comparisons involving excesses of water, realizing Noah is in the historical audience!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p23" class="">Thus, less spectacular episodes, just as good individuals with lower profiles, are &ldquo;no less serviceable&rdquo; in order to get the job done (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/48.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 48:19</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p24" class="">On a larger scale, for instance, the prophet Mormon at first thought his people were sorrowing unto repentance (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/morm/2.12-13?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Morm. 2:12&ndash;13</a>). Yet he soon discerned that theirs was not actually the sorrowing unto repentance but the &ldquo;sorrowing of the damned,&rdquo; stranding them in a &ldquo;no-man&rsquo;s-land.&rdquo; Compare that episode to the prodigal son&rsquo;s solitary working through of his own repentance; since his sorrow was real, he truly &ldquo;came to himself&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/15.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 15:17</a>). Sometimes we learn &ldquo;by sad experience,&rdquo; but sometimes not! (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/121.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 121:39</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p25" class="">Life&rsquo;s necessary defining moments come within our allotments, and we make &ldquo;on the record&rdquo; choices within these allotments. Our responses are what matter. Sufficient unto each life are the tests thereof! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/6.34?lang=eng#33" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 6:34</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p26" class="">Meanwhile, people regularly sell their souls for much less than the whole world. In Robert Bolt&rsquo;s <span class="emphasis">A Man for All Seasons,</span> Sir Thomas More is soon to be martyred, partly because his friend Rich, having been bought off by a local office, has betrayed him. More, &ldquo;looking into Rich&rsquo;s face, with pain and amusement,&rdquo; speaks: &ldquo;For Wales? Why, Richard, it profits a man nothing to give his soul for the whole world &hellip; But for Wales!&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">A Man for All Seasons</span> [1960], 92). Let this same rebuke hold for any preoccupation which preempts us from spiritual things!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p27" class="">Ponder how Jesus was and is the Lord of the universe (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/45.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 45:1</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/76.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 76:24</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/1.33?lang=eng#32" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 1:33</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/2.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 2:1</a>). Yet His ministry, as we all know, was accomplished in a very tiny geographical space. His ministerial travels were very limited. Yet therein the Savior accomplished the Atonement for all of mankind! There were certainly much more prominent hills than Golgotha and much more resplendent gardens than Gethsemane. No matter; these were sufficient to host the central act of all human history!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p28" class="">We can draw upon that glorious Atonement by repenting. We can learn to serve and to forgive within our sample of humanity, including settings no larger than the <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/05/the-importance-of-the-family?lang=eng">family</a> or friendships.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p29" class="">The justice and mercy of God will have been so demonstrably perfect that at the Final Judgment there will be no complaints, including from those who once questioned what God had allotted in the mortal framework (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/9.14-15?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 9:14&ndash;15</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.15-19?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:15&ndash;19</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/12.3-14?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 12:3&ndash;14</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/42.23-26,30?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 42:23&ndash;26, 30</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p30" class="">Hence, we can and &ldquo;ought to be content with the things allotted to us,&rdquo; being circumstantially content but without being self-satisfied and behaviorally content with ourselves (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/12.48?lang=eng#47" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 12:48</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:27</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/5.48?lang=eng#47" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 5:48</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p31" class="">Such contentment is more than shoulder-shrugging passivity. It reflects our participative assent rather than uncaring resignation.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p32" class="">The Lord knows our circumstances and the intents of our hearts, and surely the talents and gifts He has given us. He is able to gauge perfectly how we have performed within what is allotted to us, including by lifting up some of the many surrounding hands that hang down. Thus, yearning for expanded opportunities while failing to use those at hand is bad form spiritually.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p33" class="">What we could and have done within our allotted acreage, therefore, is known perfectly by the Master of the vineyard.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p34" class="">Their meekness and larger capacity for spiritual contentment may be one reason why God uses the weak of the world to accomplish His work (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/1.19,23?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 1:19, 23</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/35.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 35:13</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/133.58-59?lang=eng#57" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 133:58&ndash;59</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/1.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 1:27</a>). The worldly are usually not very interested in doing what they regard as the Lord&rsquo;s lowly work anyway.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p35" class="">Significantly, too, the Lord refuses to intimidate by sending legions of angels in order to ensure that individuals do His will (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/26.47-53?lang=eng#46" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 26:47&ndash;53</a>). His will is to be done &ldquo;because of the word,&rdquo; not because we are compelled (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/36.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 36:26</a>). The rule has been, is, and will remain &ldquo;Nevertheless, thou mayest choose for thyself&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/3.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 3:17</a>). The Lord wants conversion without intimidation.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p36" class="">Let us remember in our age of spin, the only spin God desires is our freely turning away from sin and turning to Him. Therefore, the Lord does not seek to overwhelm us but instead to help us overcome the world! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/64.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 64:2</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/rev/3.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Rev. 3:21</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p37" class="">Thus, within our allotments we see how the saintly display kindness even within barbed-wire circumstances, yet others have barbed attitudes even within opulence. Meanwhile, the discontented continue to build their own pools of self-pity, some Olympic size.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p38" class="">We see something else in Alma&rsquo;s inspired and instructive episode. Alma acknowledges that God has placed individuals in every nation who can <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/library/display/0,4945,8057-1-4424-1,00.html">preach</a> and teach His word (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/29.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 29:8</a>). Thus, if we press too much, too often, and too hard for enlarged personal roles, we could actually shrink the field of action needed by others. Furthermore, our trusting contentment lets the Holy Ghost have precious time in which to do His special work.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p39" class="">When spiritually aligned, a poise can come, even when we do not know &ldquo;the meaning of all things&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/11.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 11:17</a>). Such contented assurance produces not arrogance but quiet acceptance, which is its own form of being &ldquo;anxiously engaged&rdquo; but without all the bells and whistles (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/58.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 58:27</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/58.28?lang=eng#27" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 58:28</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p40" class="">However, this spiritual contentment rests on our accepting the Atonement of Jesus, because we &ldquo;have come to a knowledge of the goodness of God, and his matchless power, and his wisdom, and his patience, and his long-suffering towards the children of men; and also, the atonement which has been prepared from the foundation of the world&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/4.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 4:6</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p41" class="">Again, brothers and sisters, seeing Alma move from wanting to be a &ldquo;trump&rdquo; to being a humble &ldquo;instrument&rdquo; and from wanting to &ldquo;shake the earth&rdquo; to &ldquo;perhaps [bringing] some soul to repentance&rdquo; is a stunning transition! Furthermore, isn&rsquo;t it wonderful that we are permitted to grow, whether that growth is expressed in the space of nine verses or in a lifetime?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p42" class="">Colleen and I have a special granddaughter, Anna Josephine, who was born without a left hand. The other day a conversation was overheard between Anna Jo, almost five, and her cousin Talmage, three. Talmage said reassuringly as they played together, &ldquo;Anna Jo, when you grow up you will have five fingers.&rdquo; Anna Jo said, &ldquo;No, Talmage, when I grow up I won&rsquo;t have five fingers, but when I get to heaven I will have a hand.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p43" class="">If Anna Jo, who has difficult days ahead, stays steady within what has been allotted to her, she will continue to be a great blessing to many people!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/content-with-the-things-allotted-unto-us.p44" class="">How blessed we are that Alma&rsquo;s words have been preserved for all of us. May we liken Alma&rsquo;s words to ourselves (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/19.23?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 19:23</a>). I pray for this in the name of Him who counts all sparrows and all fingers and yet is the Lord of the universe, even <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>, amen!</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
